Governor of Bauchi State, Bala Muhammed, has identified nepotism as the clog in the wheel of the nation’s development. He started this on Saturday at Peoples Democratic Party(PDP) secretariat in Akure, the Ondo State capital, while addressing the party’s delegates. Muhammed, who was in the state to canvass for the support of the party’s delegates for his presidential ambition ahead of the party’s convention. -Advertisement- He emphasised on the need to restructure the federation, which he believed would address the multifaceted challenges being currently faced by the nation. According to him, “Dialogue and understanding are the only things that will ensure smooth provision of infrastructure and good governance. “Restructuring is about good governance, it is about the reconstruction of the Nigerian federation in a manner that would be efficient and acceptable to federating entities. “We are not going to be driven by mistrust and suspicion any longer. If Nigerians want Nigeria to be restructured, that is what we should do now because things are not working properly in the country. “People are feeling excluded, nepotism has taken over, and other issues. The insecurity has exposed the efficacy of our federating structure, our security architecture and so on, so we need to talk. POLL “Dialogue is part of Federation, dialogue is part of governance. Dialogue and understanding are the only things that will ensure smooth provision of infrastructure and good governance.” Analysing why he should be elected to succeed President Muhammadu Buhari, Mohammed said he’s detribalised and would carry everybody along. He emphasised that the state and local governments should be stronger for better and efficient delivery of dividends of democracy. He, however, commended the efforts of Southwest governors in tackling insecurity in the region, adding that “we need local police and reduce the power at the centre.”